  "prompt": "Which IT direct vendor companies sponsors H1B for students who went to school in USA and have experience?",
  "response": "While I can't provide a specific list of IT direct vendor companies that are sponsoring H-1B visas and targeting students who have graduated from U.S. schools, I can suggest some popular companies and sectors that are generally known for hiring international students and sponsoring H-1B visas in the IT field. You can look into the following:\n\n1. **Large Tech Companies**: \n   - Google\n   - Microsoft\n   - Amazon\n   - Apple\n   - Facebook (Meta)\n   - IBM\n\n2. **Consulting and IT Services Firms**:\n   - Accenture\n   - Deloitte\n   - Tata Consultancy Services (TCS)\n   - Cognizant\n   - Infosys\n   - Wipro\n\n3. **Startups and Mid-Sized Tech Companies**: Many startups in tech hubs like Silicon Valley, Austin, or Seattle may also sponsor H-1B visas, especially if they seek talent with specialized skills.\n\n4. **Healthcare IT Companies**: Organizations working in health technologies (like Epic Systems or Cerner) often look for tech-savvy employees and may consider international candidates.\n\n5. **Cybersecurity Firms**: Companies like Palo Alto Networks, FireEye, or CrowdStrike may also have opportunities for international students.\n\n6. **Fintech Companies**: Firms such as Square, Stripe, or PayPal often seek out tech talent and may be open to sponsorship.\n\nTo find out which specific companies are actively hiring H-1B candidates, you can use resources such as the U.S. Department of Labor's Office of Foreign Labor Certification, which maintains databases of H-1B applications. Websites like MyVisaJobs or H1Bdata.info can also show recent sponsors and their employment data.\n\nWhen considering what companies to apply to, be sure to conduct thorough research, network through alumni, attend career fairs, and join professional groups related to your field of study. This can enhance your visibility and opportunities for securing a position that offers H-1B sponsorship.",
